# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apache-ignite
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] Apache Ignite's database uses RAM as the default storage and processing tier, thus, belonging to the class of in-memory computing platforms.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] The disk tier is optional but, once enabled, will hold the full data set whereas the memory tier will cache the full or partial data set depending on its capacity.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] Data in Ignite is stored in the form of key-value pairs.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] The database component distributes key-value pairs across the cluster in such a way that every node owns a portion of the overall data set.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] Data is rebalanced automatically whenever a node is added to or removed from the cluster.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] Apache Ignite cluster can be deployed on-premises on commodity hardware, in the cloud (e.g.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] Microsoft Azure, AWS, Google Compute Engine) or in containerized and provisioning environments such as Kubernetes, Docker, Apache Mesos, VMware.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] Apache Ignite was developed by GridGain Systems, Inc. and made open source in 2014.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] GridGain continues to be the main contributor to the source code, and offers both a commercial version and professional services around Apache Ignite.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] Once donated as open source, Ignite was accepted in the Apache Incubator program in October 2014.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] The Ignite project graduated from the incubator program to become a top-level Apache project on September 18, 2015.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] In recent years, Apache Ignite has become one of the top 5 most active projects by some metrics, including user base activity and repository size.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] GridGain was founded in 2010 by Nikita Ivanov and Dmitriy Setrakyan in Pleasanton, California.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] A funding round of $2 to $3 million was disclosed in November, 2011.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] By 2013 it was located in Foster City, California when it disclosed funding of $10 million.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] Apache Ignite clustering component uses a shared nothing architecture.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] Server nodes are storage and computational units of the cluster that hold both data and indexes and process incoming requests along with computations.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] Server nodes are also known as data nodes.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] Client nodes are connection points from applications and services to the distributed database on a cluster of server nodes.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] Client nodes are usually embedded in the application code written in Java, C# or C++ that have special libraries developed.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] On top of its distributed foundation, Apache Ignite supports interfaces including JCache-compliant key-value APIs, ANSI-99 SQL with joins, ACID transactions, as well as MapReduce like computations.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] Ignite provides ODBC, JDBC and REST drivers as a way to work with the database from other programming languages or tools.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] The drivers use either client nodes or low-level socket connections internally in order to communicate to the cluster.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] Ignite database organizes data in the form of key-value pairs in distributed "caches" (the cache notion is used for historical reasons because initially, the database supported the memory tier).
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] Generally, each cache represents one entity type such as an employee or organization.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] Every cache is split into a fixed set of "partitions" that are evenly distributed among cluster nodes using the rendezvous hashing algorithm.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] There is always one primary and zero or more backup copies of a partition.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] The number of copies is configured with a replication factor parameter.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] If the full replication mode is configured, then every cluster node will store a partition's copy.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] The partitions are rebalanced automatically if a node is added to or removed from the cluster in order to achieve an even data distribution and spread the workload.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] The key-value pairs are kept in the partitions.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] Apache Ignite maps a pair to a partition by taking the key's value and passing it to a special hash function.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] The memory architecture in Apache Ignite consists of two storage tiers and is called "durable memory".
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] Internally, it uses paging for memory space management and data reference, similar to the virtual memory of systems like Unix.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] However, one significant difference between the durable and virtual memory architectures is that the former always keeps the whole data set with indexes on disk (assuming that the disk tier is enabled), while the virtual memory uses the disk when it runs out of RAM, for swapping purposes only.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] The first tier of the memory architecture, memory tier, keeps data and indexes in RAM out of Java heap in so-called "off-heap regions".
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] The regions are preallocated and managed by the database on its own which prevents Java heap utilization for storage needs, as a result, helping to avoid long garbage collection pauses.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] The regions are split into pages of fixed size that store data, indexes, and system metadata.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] Apache Ignite is fully operational from the memory tier but it is always possible to use the second tier, disk tier, for the sake of durability.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] The database comes with its own native persistence and, plus, can use RDBMS, NoSQL or Hadoop databases as its disk tier.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] Apache Ignite native persistence is a distributed and strongly consistent disk store that always holds a superset of data and indexes on disk.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] The memory tier will only cache as much data as it can depending on its capacity.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] For example, if there are 1000 entries and the memory tier can fit only 300 of them, then all 1000 will be stored on disk and only 300 will be cached in RAM.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] Persistence uses the write-ahead logging (WAL) technique for keeping immediate data modifications on disk.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] In the background, the store runs the "checkpointing process" which purpose is to copy dirty pages from the memory tier to the partition files.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] A dirty page is a page that is modified in memory with the modification recorded in WAL but not written to a respective partition file.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] The checkpointing allows removing outdated WAL segments over the time and reduces cluster restart time replaying only that part of WAL that has not been applied to the partition files.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] The native persistence became available starting version 2.1.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] Before that Apache Ignite supported only third-party databases as its disk tier.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] Apache Ignite can be configured as the in-memory tier on top of RDBMS, NoSQL or Hadoop databases speeding up the latter.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] However, there are some limitations in comparison to the native persistence.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] For instance, SQL queries will be executed only on the data that is in RAM, thus, requiring to preload all the data set from disk to memory beforehand.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] When using pure memory storage, it is possible for the data size to exceed the physical RAM size, leading to Out-Of-Memory Errors (OOMEs).
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] To avoid this, the ideal approach would be to enable Ignite native persistence or use third-party persistence.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] However, if you do not want to use native or third-party persistence, you can enable swapping, in which case, Ignite in-memory data will be moved to the swap space located on disk.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] Note that Ignite does not provide its own implementation of swap space.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] Instead, it takes advantage of the swapping functionality provided by the operating system (OS).
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] Apache Ignite is a strongly consistent platform that implements two-phase commit protocol.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] The consistency guarantees are met for both memory and disk tiers.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] Transactions in Apache Ignite are ACID-compliant and can span multiple cluster nodes and caches.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] The database supports pessimistic and optimistic concurrency modes, deadlock-free transactions and deadlock detection techniques.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] In the scenarios where transactional guarantees are optional, Apache Ignite allows executing queries in the atomic mode that provides better performance.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] Apache Ignite can be accessed using SQL APIs exposed via JDBC and ODBC drivers, and native libraries developed for Java, C#, C++ programming languages.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] Both data manipulation and data definition languages' syntax complies with ANSI-99 specification.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] Being a distributed database, Apache Ignite supports both distributed collocated and non-collocated joins.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] When the data is collocated, joins are executed on the local data of cluster nodes avoiding data movement across the network.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] Non-collocated joins might move the data sets around the network in order to prepare a consistent result set.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] Apache Ignite provides machine learning training and inference functionality as well as data preprocessing and model quality estimation.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] It natively supports classical training algorithms such as Linear Regression, Decision Trees, Random Forest, Gradient Boosting, SVM, K-Means and others.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] In addition to that, Apache Ignite has a deep integration with TensorFlow.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] This integrations allows to train neural networks on a data stored in Apache Ignite in a single-node or distributed manner.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] The key idea of Apache Ignite Machine Learning toolkit is an ability to perform distributed training and inference instantly without massive data transmissions.
[src:apache-ignite/apache-ignite] It's based on MapReduce approach, resilient to node failures and data rebalances, allows to avoid data transfers and so that speed up preprocessing and model training.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] A **data grid** is an architecture or set of services that allows users to access, modify and transfer extremely large amounts of geographically distributed data for research purposes.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] Data grids make this possible through a host of middleware applications and services that pull together data and resources from multiple administrative domains and then present it to users upon request.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] The data in a data grid can be located at a single site or multiple sites where each site can be its own administrative domain governed by a set of security restrictions as to who may access the data.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] Likewise, multiple replicas of the data may be distributed throughout the grid outside their original administrative domain and the security restrictions placed on the original data for who may access it must be equally applied to the replicas.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] Specifically developed data grid middleware is what handles the integration between users and the data they request by controlling access while making it available as efficiently as possible.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] Middleware provides all the services and applications necessary for efficient management of datasets and files within the data grid while providing users quick access to the datasets and files.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] There is a number of concepts and tools that must be available to make a data grid operationally viable.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] However, at the same time not all data grids require the same capabilities and services because of differences in access requirements, security and location of resources in comparison to users.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] In any case, most data grids will have similar middleware services that provide for a universal name space, data transport service, data access service, data replication and resource management service.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] When taken together, they are key to the data grids functional capabilities.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] A universal or unified name space makes it possible to create logical file names (LFNs) that can be referenced within the data grid that map to PFNs.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] When an LFN is requested or queried, all matching PFNs are returned to include possible replicas of the requested data.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] The end user can then choose from the returned results the most appropriate replica to use.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] This service is usually provided as part of a management system known as a Storage Resource Broker (SRB).
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] Information about the locations of files and mappings between the LFNs and PFNs may be stored in a metadata or replica catalogue.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] The replica catalogue would contain information about LFNs that map to multiple replica PFNs.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] Another middleware service is that of providing for data transport or data transfer.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] Data transport will encompass multiple functions that are not just limited to the transfer of bits, to include such items as fault tolerance and data access.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] Fault tolerance can be achieved in a data grid by providing mechanisms that ensures data transfer will resume after each interruption until all requested data is received.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] There are multiple possible methods that might be used to include starting the entire transmission over from the beginning of the data to resuming from where the transfer was interrupted.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] As an example, GridFTP provides for fault tolerance by sending data from the last acknowledged byte without starting the entire transfer from the beginning.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] The data transport service also provides for the low-level access and connections between hosts for file transfer.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] The data transport service might optionally include a network overlay function to facilitate the routing and transfer of data as well as file I/O functions that allow users to see remote files as if they were local to their system.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] The data transport service hides the complexity of access and transfer between the different systems to the user so it appears as one unified data source.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] Data access services work hand in hand with the data transfer service to provide security, access controls and management of any data transfers within the data grid.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] Security services provide mechanisms for authentication of users to ensure they are properly identified.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] Common forms of security for authentication can include the use of passwords or Kerberos (protocol).
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] Authorization services are the mechanisms that control what the user is able to access after being identified through authentication.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] Common forms of authorization mechanisms can be as simple as file permissions.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] However, need for more stringent controlled access to data is done using Access Control Lists (ACLs), Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) and Tasked-Based Authorization Controls (TBAC).
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] These types of controls can be used to provide granular access to files to include limits on access times, duration of access to granular controls that determine which files can be read or written to.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] The final data access service that might be present to protect the confidentiality of the data transport is encryption.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] The most common form of encryption for this task has been the use of SSL while in transport.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] While all of these access services operate within the data grid, access services within the various administrative domains that host the datasets will still stay in place to enforce access rules.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] The data grid access services must be in step with the administrative domains access services for this to work.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] To meet the needs for scalability, fast access and user collaboration, most data grids support replication of datasets to points within the distributed storage architecture.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] The use of replicas allows multiple users faster access to datasets and the preservation of bandwidth since replicas can often be placed strategically close to or within sites where users need them.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] However, replication of datasets and creation of replicas is bound by the availability of storage within sites and bandwidth between sites.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] The replication and creation of replica datasets is controlled by a replica management system.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] The replica management system determines user needs for replicas based on input requests and creates them based on availability of storage and bandwidth.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] All replicas are then cataloged or added to a directory based on the data grid as to their location for query by users.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] In order to perform the tasks undertaken by the replica management system, it needs to be able to manage the underlying storage infrastructure.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] The data management system will also ensure the timely updates of changes to replicas are propagated to all nodes.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] There are a number of ways the replication management system can handle the updates of replicas.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] The updates may be designed around a centralized model where a single master replica updates all others, or a decentralized model, where all peers update each other.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] The topology of node placement may also influence the updates of replicas.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] If a hierarchy topology is used then updates would flow in a tree like structure through specific paths.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] In a flat topology it is entirely a matter of the peer relationships between nodes as to how updates take place.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] In a hybrid topology consisting of both flat and hierarchy topologies updates may take place through specific paths and between peers.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] There are a number of ways the replication management system can handle the creation and placement of replicas to best serve the user community.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] If the storage architecture supports replica placement with sufficient site storage, then it becomes a matter of the needs of the users who access the datasets and a strategy for placement of replicas.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] There have been numerous strategies proposed and tested on how to best manage replica placement of datasets within the data grid to meet user requirements.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] There is not one universal strategy that fits every requirement the best.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] It is a matter of the type of data grid and user community requirements for access that will determine the best strategy to use.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] Replicas can even be created where the files are encrypted for confidentiality that would be useful in a research project dealing with medical files.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] The following section contains several strategies for replica placement.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] Dynamic replication is an approach to placement of replicas based on popularity of the data.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] The method has been designed around a hierarchical replication model.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] The data management system keeps track of available storage on all nodes.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] It also keeps track of requests (hits) for which data clients (users) in a site are requesting.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] When the number of hits for a specific dataset exceeds the replication threshold it triggers the creation of a replica on the server that directly services the user's client.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] If the direct servicing server known as a father does not have sufficient space, then the father's father in the hierarchy is then the target to receive a replica and so on up the chain until it is exhausted.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] The data management system algorithm also allows for the dynamic deletion of replicas that have a null access value or a value lower than the frequency of the data to be stored to free up space.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] This improves system performance in terms of response time, number of replicas and helps load balance across the data grid.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] This method can also use dynamic algorithms that determine whether the cost of creating the replica is truly worth the expected gains given the location.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] This method of replication like the one for dynamic replication has been designed around a hierarchical replication model found in most data grids.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] It works on a similar algorithm to dynamic replication with file access requests being a prime factor in determining which files should be replicated.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] A key difference, however, is the number and frequency of replica creations is keyed to a dynamic threshold that is computed based on request arrival rates from clients over a period of time.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] If the number of requests on average exceeds the previous threshold and shows an upward trend, and storage utilization rates indicate capacity to create more replicas, more replicas may be created.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] As with dynamic replication, the removal of replicas that have a lower threshold that were not created in the current replication interval can be removed to make space for the new replicas.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] Like the adaptive and dynamic replication methods before, fair-share replication is based on a hierarchical replication model.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] Also, like the two before, the popularity of files play a key role in determining which files will be replicated.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] The difference with this method is the placement of the replicas is based on access load and storage load of candidate servers.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] A candidate server may have sufficient storage space but be servicing many clients for access to stored files.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] Placing a replicate on this candidate could degrade performance for all clients accessing this candidate server.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] Therefore, placement of replicas with this method is done by evaluating each candidate node for access load to find a suitable node for the placement of the replica.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] If all candidate nodes are equivalently rated for access load, none or less accessed than the other, then the candidate node with the lowest storage load will be chosen to host the replicas.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] Similar methods to the other described replication methods are used to remove unused or lower requested replicates if needed.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] Replicas that are removed might be moved to a parent node for later reuse should they become popular again.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] The above three replica strategies are but three of many possible replication strategies that may be used to place replicas within the data grid where they will improve performance and access.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] Below are some others that have been proposed and tested along with the previously described replication strategies.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] Such characteristics of the data grid systems as large scale and heterogeneity require specific methods of tasks scheduling and resource allocation.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] To resolve the problem, majority of systems use extended classic methods of scheduling.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] Others invite fundamentally different methods based on incentives for autonomous nodes, like virtual money or reputation of a node.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] Another specificity of data grids, dynamics, consists in the continuous process of connecting and disconnecting of nodes and local load imbalance during an execution of tasks.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] That can make obsolete or non-optimal results of initial resource allocation for a task.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] As a result, much of the data grids utilize execution-time adaptation techniques that permit the systems to reflect to the dynamic changes: balance the load, replace disconnecting nodes, use the profit of newly connected nodes, recover a task execution after faults.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] The resource management system represents the core functionality of the data grid.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] It is the heart of the system that manages all actions related to storage resources.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] In some data grids it may be necessary to create a federated RMS architecture because of different administrative policies and a diversity of possibilities found within the data grid in place of using a single RMS.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] In such a case the RMSs in the federation will employ an architecture that allows for interoperability based on an agreed upon set of protocols for actions related to storage resources.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] Data grids have been designed with multiple topologies in mind to meet the needs of the scientific community.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] On the right are four diagrams of various topologies that have been used in data grids.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] Each topology has a specific purpose in mind for where it will be best utilized.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] Each of these topologies is further explained below.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] The need for data grids was first recognized by the scientific community concerning climate modeling, where terabyte and petabyte sized data sets were becoming the norm for transport between sites.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] More recent research requirements for data grids have been driven by the Large Hadron Collider (LHC) at CERN, the Laser Interferometer Gravitational Wave Observatory (LIGO), and the Sloan Digital Sky Survey (SDSS).
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] These examples of scientific instruments produce large amounts of data that need to be accessible by large groups of geographically dispersed researchers.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] Other uses for data grids involve governments, hospitals, schools and businesses where efforts are taking place to improve services and reduce costs by providing access to dispersed and separate data systems through the use of data grids.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] From its earliest beginnings, the concept of a Data Grid to support the scientific community was thought of as a specialized extension of the “grid” which itself was first envisioned as a way to link super computers into meta-computers.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] However, that was short lived and the grid evolved into meaning the ability to connect computers anywhere on the web to get access to any desired files and resources, similar to the way electricity is delivered over a grid by simply plugging in a device.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] The device gets electricity through its connection and the connection is not limited to a specific outlet.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] From this the data grid was proposed as an integrating architecture that would be capable of delivering resources for distributed computations.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] It would also be able to service numerous to thousands of queries at the same time while delivering gigabytes to terabytes of data for each query.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] The data grid would include its own management infrastructure capable of managing all aspects of the data grids performance and operation across multiple wide area networks while working within the existing framework known as the web.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] The data grid has also been defined more recently in terms of usability; what must a data grid be able to do in order for it to be useful to the scientific community.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] Proponents of this theory arrived at several criteria.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] One, users should be able to search and discover applicable resources within the data grid from amongst its many datasets.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] Two, users should be able to locate datasets within the data grid that are most suitable for their requirement from amongst numerous replicas.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] Three, users should be able to transfer and move large datasets between points in a short amount of time.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] Four, the data grid should provide a means to manage multiple copies of datasets within the data grid.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] And finally, the data grid should provide security with user access controls within the data grid, i.e. which users are allowed to access which data.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] The data grid is an evolving technology that continues to change and grow to meet the needs of an expanding community.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] One of the earliest programs begun to make data grids a reality was funded by the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA) in 1997 at the University of Chicago.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] This research spawned by DARPA has continued down the path to creating open source tools that make data grids possible.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] As new requirements for data grids emerge projects like the Globus Toolkit will emerge or expand to meet the gap.
[src:apache-ignite/data-grid] Data grids along with the "Grid" will continue to evolve.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] Data partitioning is a method of subdividing large sets of data into smaller chunks and distributing them between all server nodes in a balanced manner.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] Partitioning is controlled by the *affinity function*.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] The affinity function determines the mapping between keys and partitions.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] Each partition is identified by a number from a limited set (0 to 1023 by default).
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] The set of partitions is distributed between the server nodes available at the moment.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] Thus, each key is mapped to a specific node and is stored on that node.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] When the number of nodes in the cluster changes, the partitions are re-distributed — through a process called rebalancing — between the new set of nodes.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] The affinity function takes the *affinity key* as an argument.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] The affinity key can be any field of the objects stored in the cache (any column in the SQL table).
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] If the affinity key is not specified, the default key is used (in case of SQL tables, it is the PRIMARY KEY column).
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] Partitioning boosts performance by distributing both read and write operations.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] Moreover, you can design your data model in such a way that the data entries that are used together are stored together (i.e., in one partition).
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] When you request that data, only a small number of partitions is scanned.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] This technique is called Affinity Colocation.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] Partitioning helps achieve linear scalability at virtually any scale.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] You can add more nodes to the cluster as your data set grows, and Ignite makes sure that the data is distributed "equally" among all the nodes.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] The affinity function controls how data entries are mapped onto partitions and partitions onto nodes.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] The default affinity function implements the *rendezvous hashing* algorithm.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] It allows a bit of discrepancy in the partition-to-node mapping (i.e., some nodes may be responsible for a slightly larger number of partitions than others).
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] However, the affinity function guarantees that when the topology changes, partitions are migrated only to the new node that joined or from the node that left.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] No data exchange happens between the remaining nodes.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] When creating a cache or SQL table, you can choose between partitioned and replicated mode of cache operation.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] The two modes are designed for different use case scenarios and provide different performance and availability benefits.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] In this mode, all partitions are split equally between all server nodes.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] This mode is the most scalable distributed cache mode and allows you to store as much data as fits in the total memory (RAM and disk) available across all nodes.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] Essentially, the more nodes you have, the more data you can store.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] Unlike the `REPLICATED` mode, where updates are expensive because every node in the cluster needs to be updated, with `PARTITIONED` mode, updates become cheap because only one primary node (and optionally 1 or more backup nodes) need to be updated for every key.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] However, reads are somewhat more expensive because only certain nodes have the data cached.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] The picture below illustrates the distribution of a partitioned cache.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] Essentially we have key A assigned to a node running in JVM1, key B assigned to a node running in JVM3, etc.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] In the `REPLICATED` mode, all the data (every partition) is replicated to every node in the cluster.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] This cache mode provides the utmost availability of data as it is available on every node.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] However, every data update must be propagated to all other nodes, which can impact performance and scalability.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] In the diagram below, the node running in JVM1 is a primary node for key A, but it also stores backup copies for all other keys as well (B, C, D).
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] Because the same data is stored on all cluster nodes, the size of a replicated cache is limited by the amount of memory (RAM and disk) available on the node.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] This mode is ideal for scenarios where cache reads are a lot more frequent than cache writes, and data sets are small.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] If your system does cache lookups over 80% of the time, then you should consider using the `REPLICATED` cache mode.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] By default, Ignite keeps a single copy of each partition (a single copy of the entire data set).
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] In this case, if one or multiple nodes become unavailable, you lose access to partitions stored on these nodes.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] To avoid this, you can configure Ignite to maintain backup copies of each partition.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] Backup copies are configured per cache (table).
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] If you configure 2 backup copies, the cluster maintains 3 copies of each partition.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] One of the partitions is called the *primary* partition, and the other two are called *backup* partitions.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] By extension, the node that has the primary partition is called the *primary node for the keys stored in the partition*.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] The node with backup partitions is called the *backup node*.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] When a node with the primary partition for some key leaves the cluster, Ignite triggers the partition map exchange (PME) process.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] PME labels one of the backup partitions (if they are configured) for the key as primary.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] Backup partitions increase the availability of your data, and in some cases, the speed of read operations, since Ignite reads data from backed-up partitions if they are available on the local node (this is the default behavior that can be disabled.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] However, they also increase memory consumption or the size of the persistent storage (if enabled).
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] Partition map exchange (PME) is a process of sharing information about partition distribution (partition map) across the cluster so that every node knows where to look for specific keys.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] PME is required whenever the partition distribution for any cache changes, for example, when new nodes are added to the topology or old nodes leave the topology (whether on user request or due to a failure).
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] When one of the PME-triggering events occurs, the cluster waits for all ongoing transactions to complete and then starts PME.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] Also, during PME, new transactions are postponed until the process finishes.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] The PME process works in the following way: The coordinator node requests from all nodes the information about the partitions they own.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] Each node sends this information to the coordinator.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] Once the coordinator node receives the messages from all nodes, it merges the information into a full partition map and sends it to all nodes.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] When the coordinator has received confirmation messages from all nodes, PME is considered completed.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] Refer to the Data Rebalancing page for details.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] It may happen that throughout the cluster’s lifecycle, some of the data partitions are lost due to the failure of some primary node and backup nodes that held a copy of the partitions.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] Such a situation leads to a partial data loss and needs to be addressed according to your use case.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] For detailed information about partition loss policies, see Partition Loss Policy.
[src:apache-ignite/data-partitioning] Apache, Apache Ignite, the Apache feather and the Apache Ignite logo are either registered trademarks or trademarks of The Apache Software Foundation.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-cache] In computing, a **distributed cache** is an extension of the traditional concept of cache used in a single locale.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-cache] A distributed cache may span multiple servers so that it can grow in size and in transactional capacity.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-cache] It is mainly used to store application data residing in database and web session data.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-cache] The idea of distributed caching has become feasible now because main memory has become very cheap and network cards have become very fast, with 1 Gbit now standard everywhere and 10 Gbit gaining traction.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-cache] Also, a distributed cache works well on lower cost machines usually employed for web servers as opposed to database servers which require expensive hardware.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-cache] An emerging internet architecture known as Information-centric networking (ICN) is one of the best examples of a distributed cache network.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-cache] The ICN is a network level solution hence the existing distributed network cache management schemes are not well suited for ICN.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-cache] In the supercomputer environment, distributed cache is typically implemented in the form of burst buffer.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-cache] In distributed caching, each cache key is assigned to a specific shard (a.k.a. partition).
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] The components of a distributed system communicate and coordinate their actions by passing messages to one another in order to achieve a common goal.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Three challenges of distributed systems are: maintaining concurrency of components, overcoming the lack of a global clock, and managing the independent failure of components.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] When a component of one system fails, the entire system does not fail.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Examples of distributed systems vary from SOA-based systems to microservices to massively multiplayer online games to peer-to-peer applications.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Distributed systems cost more than monolithic architectures, primarily due to increased needs for additional hardware, servers, gateways, firewalls, new subnets, proxies, and so on.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Distributed systems can also suffer from fallacies of distributed computing.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Conversely, a well-designed distributed system is more scalable, more durable, more changeable, and more fine-tuned than a monolithic application deployed on a single machine.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] According to Marc Brooker: "a system is scalable in the range where marginal cost of additional workload is nearly constant." Serverless technologies fit this definition but the total cost of ownership, and not just the infrastructure cost must be considered.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] A computer program that runs within a distributed system is called a **distributed program**, and *distributed programming* is the process of writing such programs.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] There are many types of implementations for the message-passing mechanism, including pure HTTP, RPC-like connectors, and message queues.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] The word *distributed* in terms such as "distributed system", "distributed programming", and "distributed algorithm" originally referred to computer networks where individual computers were physically distributed within some geographical area.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] The terms are nowadays used in a much wider sense, even referring to autonomous processes that run on the same physical computer and interact with each other by message passing.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] A distributed system may have a common goal, such as solving a large computational problem; the user then perceives the collection of autonomous processors as a unit.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Alternatively, each computer may have its own user with individual needs, and the purpose of the distributed system is to coordinate the use of shared resources or provide communication services to the users.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] In distributed systems, events represent a fact or state change (e.g., *OrderPlaced*) and are typically broadcast asynchronously to multiple consumers, promoting loose coupling and scalability.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] While events generally don't expect an immediate response, acknowledgment mechanisms are often implemented at the infrastructure level (e.g., Kafka commit offsets, SNS delivery statuses) rather than being an inherent part of the event pattern itself.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] In contrast, messages serve a broader role, encompassing commands (e.g., *ProcessPayment*), events (e.g., *PaymentProcessed*), and documents (e.g., *DataPayload*).
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Both events and messages can support various delivery guarantees, including at-least-once, at-most-once, and exactly-once, depending on the technology stack and implementation.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] However, exactly-once delivery is often achieved through idempotency mechanisms rather than true, infrastructure-level exactly-once semantics.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Delivery patterns for both events and messages include publish/subscribe (one-to-many) and point-to-point (one-to-one).
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] While request/reply is technically possible, it is more commonly associated with messaging patterns rather than pure event-driven systems.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Events excel at state propagation and decoupled notifications, while messages are better suited for command execution, workflow orchestration, and explicit coordination.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Modern architectures commonly combine both approaches, leveraging events for distributed state change notifications and messages for targeted command execution and structured workflows based on specific timing, ordering, and delivery requirements.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Distributed systems are groups of networked computers which share a common goal for their work.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] The terms "concurrent computing", "parallel computing", and "distributed computing" have much overlap, and no clear distinction exists between them.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] The same system may be characterized both as "parallel" and "distributed"; the processors in a typical distributed system run concurrently in parallel.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Parallel computing may be seen as a particularly tightly coupled form of distributed computing, and distributed computing may be seen as a loosely coupled form of parallel computing.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] The figure on the right illustrates the difference between distributed and parallel systems.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Figure (a) is a schematic view of a typical distributed system; the system is represented as a network topology in which each node is a computer and each line connecting the nodes is a communication link.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Figure (b) shows the same distributed system in more detail: each computer has its own local memory, and information can be exchanged only by passing messages from one node to another by using the available communication links.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Figure (c) shows a parallel system in which each processor has a direct access to a shared memory.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] The situation is further complicated by the traditional uses of the terms parallel and distributed *algorithm* that do not quite match the above definitions of parallel and distributed *systems* (see below for more detailed discussion).
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Nevertheless, as a rule of thumb, high-performance parallel computation in a shared-memory multiprocessor uses parallel algorithms while the coordination of a large-scale distributed system uses distributed algorithms.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] The use of concurrent processes which communicate through message-passing has its roots in operating system architectures studied in the 1960s.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] The first widespread distributed systems were local-area networks such as Ethernet, which was invented in the 1970s.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] ARPANET, one of the predecessors of the Internet, was introduced in the late 1960s, and ARPANET e-mail was invented in the early 1970s.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] E-mail became the most successful application of ARPANET, and it is probably the earliest example of a large-scale distributed application.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] In addition to ARPANET (and its successor, the global Internet), other early worldwide computer networks included Usenet and FidoNet from the 1980s, both of which were used to support distributed discussion systems.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] The study of distributed computing became its own branch of computer science in the late 1970s and early 1980s.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] The first conference in the field, Symposium on Principles of Distributed Computing (PODC), dates back to 1982, and its counterpart International Symposium on Distributed Computing (DISC) was first held in Ottawa in 1985 as the International Workshop on Distributed Algorithms on Graphs.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Various hardware and software architectures are used for distributed computing.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] At a lower level, it is necessary to interconnect multiple CPUs with some sort of network, regardless of whether that network is printed onto a circuit board or made up of loosely coupled devices and cables.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] At a higher level, it is necessary to interconnect processes running on those CPUs with some sort of communication system.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Distributed programming typically falls into one of several basic architectures: client–server, three-tier, *n*-tier, or peer-to-peer; or categories: loose coupling, or tight coupling.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Another basic aspect of distributed computing architecture is the method of communicating and coordinating work among concurrent processes.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Through various message passing protocols, processes may communicate directly with one another, typically in a main/sub relationship.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Alternatively, a "database-centric" architecture can enable distributed computing to be done without any form of direct inter-process communication, by utilizing a shared database.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Database-centric architecture in particular provides relational processing analytics in a schematic architecture allowing for live environment relay.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] This enables distributed computing functions both within and beyond the parameters of a networked database.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Cell-based architecture is a distributed computing approach in which computational resources are organized into self-contained units called cells.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Each cell operates independently, processing requests while maintaining scalability, fault isolation, and availability.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] A cell typically consists of multiple services or application components and functions as an autonomous unit.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Some implementations replicate entire sets of services across multiple cells, while others partition workloads between cells.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] In replicated models, requests may be rerouted to an operational cell if another experiences a failure.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] This design is intended to enhance system resilience by reducing the impact of localized failures.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Some implementations employ circuit breakers within and between cells.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Within a cell, circuit breakers may be used to prevent cascading failures among services, while inter-cell circuit breakers can isolate failing cells and redirect traffic to those that remain operational.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Cell-based architecture has been adopted in some large-scale distributed systems, particularly in cloud-native and high-availability environments, where fault isolation and redundancy are key design considerations.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Its implementation varies depending on system requirements, infrastructure constraints, and operational objectives.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] According to Reactive Manifesto, reactive distributed systems are responsive, resilient, elastic and message-driven.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Subsequently, Reactive systems are more flexible, loosely-coupled and scalable.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] To make your systems reactive, you are advised to implement Reactive Principles.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Reactive Principles are a set of principles and patterns which help to make your cloud native application as well as edge native applications more reactive.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Many tasks that we would like to automate by using a computer are of question–answer type: we would like to ask a question and the computer should produce an answer.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] In theoretical computer science, such tasks are called computational problems.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Formally, a computational problem consists of *instances* together with a *solution* for each instance.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Instances are questions that we can ask, and solutions are desired answers to these questions.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Theoretical computer science seeks to understand which computational problems can be solved by using a computer (computability theory) and how efficiently (computational complexity theory).
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Traditionally, it is said that a problem can be solved by using a computer if we can design an algorithm that produces a correct solution for any given instance.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Such an algorithm can be implemented as a computer program that runs on a general-purpose computer: the program reads a problem instance from input, performs some computation, and produces the solution as output.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Formalisms such as random-access machines or universal Turing machines can be used as abstract models of a sequential general-purpose computer executing such an algorithm.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] The field of concurrent and distributed computing studies similar questions in the case of either multiple computers, or a computer that executes a network of interacting processes: which computational problems can be solved in such a network and how efficiently?
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] However, it is not at all obvious what is meant by "solving a problem" in the case of a concurrent or distributed system: for example, what is the task of the algorithm designer, and what is the concurrent or distributed equivalent of a sequential general-purpose computer?
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] The discussion below focuses on the case of multiple computers, although many of the issues are the same for concurrent processes running on a single computer.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] In the case of distributed algorithms, computational problems are typically related to graphs.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Often the graph that describes the structure of the computer network *is* the problem instance.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] This is illustrated in the following example.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Consider the computational problem of finding a coloring of a given graph *G*.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] While the field of parallel algorithms has a different focus than the field of distributed algorithms, there is much interaction between the two fields.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] For example, the Cole–Vishkin algorithm for graph coloring was originally presented as a parallel algorithm, but the same technique can also be used directly as a distributed algorithm.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Moreover, a parallel algorithm can be implemented either in a parallel system (using shared memory) or in a distributed system (using message passing).
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] The traditional boundary between parallel and distributed algorithms (choose a suitable network vs. run in any given network) does not lie in the same place as the boundary between parallel and distributed systems (shared memory vs. message passing).
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] In parallel algorithms, yet another resource in addition to time and space is the number of computers.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Indeed, often there is a trade-off between the running time and the number of computers: the problem can be solved faster if there are more computers running in parallel (see speedup).
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] If a decision problem can be solved in polylogarithmic time by using a polynomial number of processors, then the problem is said to be in the class NC.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] The class NC can be defined equally well by using the PRAM formalism or Boolean circuits—PRAM machines can simulate Boolean circuits efficiently and vice versa.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] In the analysis of distributed algorithms, more attention is usually paid on communication operations than computational steps.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Perhaps the simplest model of distributed computing is a synchronous system where all nodes operate in a lockstep fashion.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] This model is commonly known as the LOCAL model.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] During each *communication round*, all nodes in parallel (1) receive the latest messages from their neighbours, (2) perform arbitrary local computation, and (3) send new messages to their neighbors.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] In such systems, a central complexity measure is the number of synchronous communication rounds required to complete the task.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] This complexity measure is closely related to the diameter of the network.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] On the one hand, any computable problem can be solved trivially in a synchronous distributed system in approximately 2*D* communication rounds: simply gather all information in one location (*D* rounds), solve the problem, and inform each node about the solution (*D* rounds).
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] On the other hand, if the running time of the algorithm is much smaller than *D* communication rounds, then the nodes in the network must produce their output without having the possibility to obtain information about distant parts of the network.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] In other words, the nodes must make globally consistent decisions based on information that is available in their *local D-neighbourhood*.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Many distributed algorithms are known with the running time much smaller than *D* rounds, and understanding which problems can be solved by such algorithms is one of the central research questions of the field.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Typically an algorithm which solves a problem in polylogarithmic time in the network size is considered efficient in this model.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Another commonly used measure is the total number of bits transmitted in the network (cf. communication complexity).
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] The features of this concept are typically captured with the CONGEST(B) model, which is similarly defined as the LOCAL model, but where single messages can only contain B bits.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Traditional computational problems take the perspective that the user asks a question, a computer (or a distributed system) processes the question, then produces an answer and stops.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] However, there are also problems where the system is required not to stop, including the dining philosophers problem and other similar mutual exclusion problems.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] In these problems, the distributed system is supposed to continuously coordinate the use of shared resources so that no conflicts or deadlocks occur.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] There are also fundamental challenges that are unique to distributed computing, for example those related to *fault-tolerance*.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Examples of related problems include consensus problems, Byzantine fault tolerance, and self-stabilisation.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Note that in distributed systems, latency should be measured through "99th percentile" because "median" and "average" can be misleading.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] The network nodes communicate among themselves in order to decide which of them will get into the "coordinator" state.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] For that, they need some method in order to break the symmetry among them.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] For example, if each node has unique and comparable identities, then the nodes can compare their identities, and decide that the node with the highest identity is the coordinator.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] The definition of this problem is often attributed to LeLann, who formalized it as a method to create a new token in a token ring network in which the token has been lost.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Coordinator election algorithms are designed to be economical in terms of total bytes transmitted, and time.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] The algorithm suggested by Gallager, Humblet, and Spira for general undirected graphs has had a strong impact on the design of distributed algorithms in general, and won the Dijkstra Prize for an influential paper in distributed computing.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Many other algorithms were suggested for different kinds of network graphs, such as undirected rings, unidirectional rings, complete graphs, grids, directed Euler graphs, and others.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] A general method that decouples the issue of the graph family from the design of the coordinator election algorithm was suggested by Korach, Kutten, and Moran.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] In order to perform coordination, distributed systems employ the concept of coordinators.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] The coordinator election problem is to choose a process from among a group of processes on different processors in a distributed system to act as the central coordinator.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] Several central coordinator election algorithms exist.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] So far the focus has been on *designing* a distributed system that solves a given problem.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] A complementary research problem is *studying* the properties of a given distributed system.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] The halting problem is an analogous example from the field of centralised computation: we are given a computer program and the task is to decide whether it halts or runs forever.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] The halting problem is undecidable in the general case, and naturally understanding the behaviour of a computer network is at least as hard as understanding the behaviour of one computer.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] However, there are many interesting special cases that are decidable.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] In particular, it is possible to reason about the behaviour of a network of finite-state machines.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] One example is telling whether a given network of interacting (asynchronous and non-deterministic) finite-state machines can reach a deadlock.
[src:apache-ignite/distributed-computing] This problem is PSPACE-complete, i.e., it is decidable, but not likely that there is an efficient (centralised, parallel or distributed) algorithm that solves the problem in the case of large networks.
[src:apache-ignite/in-memory-database] An **in-memory database** (**IMDb**, or **main memory database system** (**MMDB**) or **memory resident database**) is a database management system that primarily relies on main memory for computer data storage.
[src:apache-ignite/in-memory-database] It is contrasted with database management systems that employ a disk storage mechanism.
[src:apache-ignite/in-memory-database] In-memory databases are faster than disk-optimized databases because disk access is slower than memory access and the internal optimization algorithms are simpler and execute fewer CPU instructions.
[src:apache-ignite/in-memory-database] Accessing data in memory eliminates seek time when querying the data, which provides faster and more predictable performance than disk.
[src:apache-ignite/in-memory-database] Applications where response time is critical, such as those running telecommunications network equipment and mobile advertising networks, often use main-memory databases.
[src:apache-ignite/in-memory-database] IMDBs have gained much traction, especially in the data analytics space, starting in the mid-2000s – mainly due to multi-core processors that can address large memory and due to less expensive RAM.
[src:apache-ignite/in-memory-database] A potential technical hurdle with in-memory data storage is the volatility of RAM.
[src:apache-ignite/in-memory-database] Specifically in the event of a power loss, intentional or otherwise, data stored in volatile RAM is lost.
[src:apache-ignite/in-memory-database] With the introduction of non-volatile random-access memory technology, in-memory databases will be able to run at full speed and maintain data in the event of power failure.
[src:apache-ignite/in-memory-database] In its simplest form, main memory databases store data on volatile memory devices.
[src:apache-ignite/in-memory-database] These devices lose all stored information when the device loses power or is reset.
[src:apache-ignite/in-memory-database] In this case, IMDBs can be said to lack support for the "durability" portion of the ACID (atomicity, consistency, isolation, durability) properties.
[src:apache-ignite/in-memory-database] Volatile memory-based IMDBs can, and often do, support the other three ACID properties of atomicity, consistency and isolation.
[src:apache-ignite/in-memory-database] While storing data in-memory confers performance advantages, it is an expensive method of data storage.
[src:apache-ignite/in-memory-database] An approach to realising the benefits of in-memory storage while limiting its costs is to store the most frequently accessed data in-memory and the rest on disk.
[src:apache-ignite/in-memory-database] Since there is no hard distinction between which data should be stored in-memory and which should be stored on disk, some systems dynamically update where data is stored based on the data's usage.
[src:apache-ignite/in-memory-database] This approach is subtly different from caching, in which the most *recently accessed* data is cached, as opposed to the most *frequently accessed* data being stored in-memory.
[src:apache-ignite/in-memory-database] In the cloud computing industry the terms "data temperature", or "hot data" and "cold data" have emerged to describe how data is stored in this respect.
[src:apache-ignite/in-memory-database] Hot data is used to describe mission-critical data that needs to be accessed frequently while cold data describes data that is needed less often and less urgently, such as data kept for archiving or auditing purposes.
[src:apache-ignite/in-memory-database] Hot data should be stored in ways offering fast retrieval and modification, often accomplished by in-memory storage but not always.
[src:apache-ignite/in-memory-database] Cold data on the other hand can be stored in a more cost-effective way and is accepted that data access will likely be slower compared to hot data.
[src:apache-ignite/in-memory-database] While these descriptions are useful, "hot" and "cold" lack concrete definitions.
[src:apache-ignite/in-memory-database] Manufacturing efficiency provides another reason for selecting a combined in-memory/on-disk database system.
[src:apache-ignite/in-memory-database] Some device product lines, especially in consumer electronics, include some units with permanent storage, and others that rely on memory for storage (set-top boxes, for example).
[src:apache-ignite/in-memory-database] If such devices require a database system, a manufacturer can adopt a hybrid database system at lower and *upper* cost, and with less customization of code, rather than using separate in-memory and on-disk databases, respectively, for its disk-less and disk-based products.
[src:apache-ignite/in-memory-database] The first database engine to support both in-memory and on-disk tables in a single database, WebDNA, was released in 1995.
[src:apache-ignite/in-memory-database] Another variation involves large amounts of nonvolatile memory in the server, for example, flash memory chips as addressable memory rather than structured as disk arrays.
[src:apache-ignite/in-memory-database] A database in this form of memory combines very fast access speed with persistence over reboots and power losses.
[src:apache-ignite/latest] Apache Ignite 3 is a distributed database for high-performance computing with in-memory speed.
