[src:apache-ignite/memory-architecture] Ignite memory architecture allows storing and processing data and indexes both in memory and on disk, and helps achieve in-memory performance with the durability of disk.
[src:apache-ignite/memory-architecture] The multi-tiered storage operates in a way similar to the virtual memory of operating systems, such as Linux.
[src:apache-ignite/memory-architecture] Multi-tiered architecture is a page-based memory architecture that is split into pages of fixed size.
[src:apache-ignite/memory-architecture] The pages are stored in *managed off-heap regions* in RAM (outside of Java heap) and are organized in a special hierarchy on disk.
[src:apache-ignite/memory-architecture] Ignite maintains the same binary data representation both in memory and on disk.
[src:apache-ignite/memory-architecture] This removes the need for costly serialization when moving data between memory and disk.
[src:apache-ignite/memory-architecture] The picture below illustrates the architecture of the multi-tiered storage.
[src:apache-ignite/memory-architecture] Every data region starts with an initial size and has a maximum size it can grow to.
[src:apache-ignite/memory-architecture] The region expands to its maximum size by allocating continuous memory segments.
[src:apache-ignite/memory-architecture] A memory segment is a continuous byte array or physical memory allocated from the operating system.
[src:apache-ignite/memory-architecture] The array is divided into pages of fixed size.
[src:apache-ignite/memory-architecture] There are several types of pages that can reside in the segment, as shown in the picture below.
[src:apache-ignite/memory-architecture] A data page stores entries you put into caches from the application side.
[src:apache-ignite/memory-architecture] Usually, a single data page holds multiple key-value entries in order to use the memory as efficiently as possible and avoid memory fragmentation.
[src:apache-ignite/memory-architecture] When a new entry is added to a cache, Ignite looks for an optimal page that can fit the whole key-value entry.
[src:apache-ignite/memory-architecture] However, if an entry’s total size exceeds the page size configured via the `DataStorageConfiguration.setPageSize(..)` property, then the entry occupies more than one data page.
[src:apache-ignite/memory-architecture] If during an update an entry size expands beyond the free space available in its data page, then Ignite searches for a new data page that has enough room to take the updated entry and moves the entry there.
[src:apache-ignite/memory-architecture] Ignite performs memory defragmentation automatically and does not require any explicit action from a user.
[src:apache-ignite/memory-architecture] Over time, an individual data page might be updated multiple times by different CRUD operations.
[src:apache-ignite/memory-architecture] This can lead to the page and overall memory fragmentation.
[src:apache-ignite/memory-architecture] To minimize memory fragmentation, Ignite uses *page compaction* whenever a page becomes too fragmented.
[src:apache-ignite/memory-architecture] The page has a header that stores information needed for internal usage.
[src:apache-ignite/memory-architecture] All key-value entries are always added from right to left.
[src:apache-ignite/memory-architecture] In the picture, there are three entries (1, 2 and 3 respectively) stored in the page.
[src:apache-ignite/memory-architecture] These entries might have different size.
[src:apache-ignite/memory-architecture] The offsets (or references) to the entries' locations inside the page are stored left-to-right and are always of fixed size.
[src:apache-ignite/memory-architecture] The offsets are used as pointers to look up the key-value entries in a page.
[src:apache-ignite/memory-architecture] The space in the middle is a free space and is filled in whenever more data is pushed into the cluster.
[src:apache-ignite/memory-architecture] This is what a fragmented page looks like.
[src:apache-ignite/memory-architecture] However, when the whole free space available in the page is needed or some fragmentation threshold is reached, the compaction process defragments the page turning it into the state shown in the first picture above, where the free space is continuous.
[src:apache-ignite/memory-architecture] This process is automatic and doesn’t require any action from the user side.
[src:apache-ignite/memory-architecture] Ignite provides a number of features that let you persist your data on disk with consistency guarantees.
[src:apache-ignite/memory-architecture] You can restart the cluster without losing the data, be resilient to crashes, and provide a storage for data when the amount of RAM is not sufficient.
[src:apache-ignite/memory-architecture] When native persistence is enabled, Ignite always stores all the data on disk, and loads as much data as it can into RAM for processing.
[src:apache-ignite/memory-architecture] Refer to the Ignite Persistence section for further information.
